Spatial Analysis of Airbnb Listings in Berlin¶

P. Rudolph, C. Brendel¶

February 27th, 2019¶

Abstract¶

Airbnb accommodations can be found in every district of Berlin. Accommodation prices can vary vastly due to individual characteristics such as size and condition of the offered room or apartment. Nevertheless, spatial factors play a significant role, too. Accommodations located closer to the center and the sights are more expensive than their counterparts in the outer regions of the city. Furthermore, Berlin was divided into West and East Berlin until 1990 leading to a socioeconomical gap between those parts. Still, there are some exceptions.

Introduction¶

Berlin has become one of the top tourist destination in the world with approximately 12 millions of tourists each year. All of those tourists need an accomodation for their stay in Berlin. Most of them choose to use the website “Airbnb”, in order to find their accommodation. Indeed, Airbnb attracts hosts and guests with its competitive prices and unique experiences. In Germany, Berlin is an unchallenged Airbnb capital, more flats and rooms are offered than in Hamburg, Munich, Cologne and Frankfurt combined. In 2014, approximately 11700 accommodation units are offered for rental in Berlin each day. According to the latest data published by airbnb there is a ratio of 1 in 200 flats can be found on Airbnb. However, not all neighbourhoods are equally popular when it comes to Airbnb rentals. The map below shows in which parts of Berlin most flats and rooms are offered. This reveals considerable differences between neighbourhoods.


Figure 1. Number of listings per district | Source: http://www.airbnbvsberlin.com

Hypothesis¶

In this report, we have decided to focus on the differences in pricing of the Airbnb offers between the districts in Berlin. We believe that there is even higher discrepancy between the different neighbourhoods because of the varying amount of rooms or whole apartments. Still, we will try to see if there is a difference between the city center and the suburbs. As well, due to the historical context, such as the division by the Allies that was later enforced by the Berlin Wall, which separated Berlin into East and West for almost thirty years. We can wonder if there is a discrepancy between East and West Berlin in terms of prices for Airbnb accommodations as well.


Figure 2. The wall going through Berlin | Source: http://annikamarlenhinze.com/images/Berlinhoods_web.jpg


Figure 3. Map of Berlin | Source: https://reise.naanoo.de/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/berlin-bezirke-karte.jpg

Methods¶

Clustering¶

For creating the spatial weights we used the rook contiguity and the euclidian distance based spatial weights. The rook contiguity has a lower p-value than the Euclidian Distance based method. Both methods show different results. While the rook contiguity shows only Müggelheim as a relevant cluster in the southeast of Berlin, the euclidian contiguity shows also Schmöckwitz and Grünau. In our non-mathmetical analysis Schmöckwitz seems highly significant, having the highest median price for any district in Berlin.

Visualization¶

For the visualization of the individual Airbnb listings in Berlin we used Python and the Geopandas, Pandas, Matplotlib and Numpy libraries. The prices are seperated in three different types:

  • Accommodation Types:

    • Low Priced (16-30€)

    • Medium Priced (31-120€)

    • High Priced (121-241€)

The data for the Airbnb listings includes a lot of erroneous values; for instance, rooms for only one night for 1 € or accomodations for 60.000 € a night. These values are cut out.

Correlation between average rent per m2 and Airbnb prices¶

Sadly, we couldn't obtain a useful dataset for the average rent in Berlin for a correlation analysis with the median prices of the different districts in Berlin. Further data analysis requires this kind of dataset.

Results¶


Figure 4. Percentile map of median Airbnb prices in Berlin


Average rent in Euro per m2 | Source: https://www.immobilienscout24.de/content/dam/is24/ibw/dokumente/berlin.png

As you can see in Figure 3., the prices for an accommodation are generally lower in the eastern part of Berlin, still Berlin Schmöckewitz in the southeastern area is standing out, as it is the most expensive district for accommodations in Berlin.

On the map shown in Figure 3. you can also see the trend that the city center/downtown has the highest prices for accommodation after Berlin Schmöckewitz. The trend of the price structure in the center is comparable to an onion, having the highest prices in the inner peel and a gradient towards lower prices with every peel going out from the center.

Rook Cluster¶


Figure 5. Rook clustered map showing significant districts

The Rook Cluster shows us High-Low districts in the east of Berlin and a High-High cluster in the center. In the north and south you can see Low-Low clusters and in the southeast you can see a Low-High district. The further west of Berlin does not show any significance.


Figure 6. Map showing the significance


Figure 7. Lisa Scatter Plot Frame

The Moran's value of ~0.1 can indicate that there is only a small amount of clustering in Berlin.

Discussion¶

Both clustering approaches result in a similar map but there are still differences. For instance, the Rook Contiguity does not present Schmöckewitz as a significant district, the method using the Euclidian Distance does. The other parts show some smaller differences, too, with the city center being a bigger cluster in the Euclidian Distance approach.

While the center has the highest density of expensive accommodations,Schmöckewitz has the highest median price of all the districts although it located at the southeastern border to the state Brandenburg. This is against both of our stated trends. There has to be a reason for these high prices. Further investigations show that the accomodations in Berlin Schmöckewitz are atleast very big in comparison to the average listing but are sometimes whole houses. This explains why the prices for these accomodations are very high. The individual visualization shows that there is no accomodation for below 30 € in Schmöckewitz and that there are a lot of offers for over 100 €.

When you compare the average Airbnb price in Schmöckwitz to the average rent per m2, you can see that they do not correlate too much. While the average rent per m2 is not high, the average Airbnb price is highest. Schmöckwitz is a renown local recreation area which could lead to an increase of the accommodation's price.

Making correlations at this moment with this data is proofing difficult because the Airbnb prices do not show the amount of m2 the accommodations offer. This can lead to many wrong conclusions. In addition, some districts do only offer a small amount of Airbnb listings and are vulnerable too high or low individual values.

The clustering method shows us that the variance in terms of average prices is higher in the eastern part of Berlin. Expensive districts are located directly next to cheap districts. The average prices in west Berlin have a lower variance; significant clusters are less existent.

Conclusion/Summary¶

Even though there is a general trend in average prices for accommodations going from very high in the center to very low in the suburbs, there are still districts breaking out of this trend. Accommodation size does also play a massive role that we cannot cover with our data. In addition, districts with very few listings are vulnerable for a high standard error caused by a varying size and condition of the apartment.

Our hypothesis that accommodations in the east are cheaper is only partly true. The most expensive district is located in the southeast of Berlin. Furthermore, the Rook Cluster shows that there is a high variation between the districts in the east. Expensive districts for Airbnb are located right next to cheap districts.
